  caseStudy="One thing we run into constantly in the older pockets of Newhall and Saugus is a pool that looks fine from the surface, chalky plaster, some staining, nothing alarming, until we start testing water flow and find pressure loss at the equipment pad. More often than not, the plumbing underneath is original to the house, and by the time the plaster is due for a replaster anyway, the pipe is right behind it. When that happens, we always walk homeowners through both jobs together. Replacing plaster without addressing plumbing that's already failing just means digging the same yard up again in a year or two. It costs more up front to do both at once, but it's the honest recommendation, and it's one we make often in this part of Santa Clarita."
